As shown in Fig. 1, the only input materials for this molten salt electrodeposition of crystalline silicon films are abundant and low-cost silicon dioxide, calcium oxide and calcium chloride. Additional experimental details for the production of high-purity silicon films and reaction mechanisms can be found in Methods, Supplementary Tables 1 and 2, and Supplementary Figs. 1–6. Calcium oxide is added as an intermediate for continuing ionization of silicon dioxide to form silicate ions (expressed as SiOyn−, including SiO32−, SiO44−, etc.), which are then electrodeposited onto substrates to form crystalline silicon films. The general reactions for the electrodeposition process can be simply expressed as follows:1xSiO2+yCaOCa2+,O2−→CaySixO(2x+y)yCa2+,SixO(2x+y)2y−\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
